Escape: "Every refugee woman has experience with sexual violence"
Sexual violence is almost part of everyday life for women who flee alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house offers refuge.
There are four women in a large kitchen.
Each has a baby with him who is at most one year old.
One of them put her young son in her arm.
He looks into the room with big eyes.
His mother is staring at the table top.
Until she realizes she's being watched.
She smiles briefly and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until you talk to Katrin Bahr.
She is the managing director of Condrobs, a social assistance provider in Bavaria, and deals with the topic of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralized accommodations for women alone and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and Munich’s Frauenhilfe.
It was recently officially opened.
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a security guard outside the door.
"It's not an exaggeration to say: every woman who arrives here has had experiences with sexual violence on her escape," Bahr says.
"Men flee because of wars because they are politically persecuted, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as hopefuls," she recounts.
In women, other reasons for the escape prevail: "Many steal from it secretly because they see no other way out".
In their homeland, they have had experience with sexual violence, forced marriages, honor killings, slavery or forced prostitution.
That's what drives them away.
On the run, this continues.
"That smugglers, for example, are calling for a sexual act for a bottle of water is not uncommon," Bahr says.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Anyone who thinks that will end as soon as they arrive in Germany is crazy, says Bahr.
Here, too, single women in refugee shelters are often considered inferior and, at worst, abused.
This leads to the fact that about 90 percent of women who live in the accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized, she estimates.
“Some of the children certainly did not come into being voluntarily.”
Many women are so used to say nothing.
“Or they don’t dare to talk openly about what they have experienced, because the shame is too great.”
Since they often do not know how to help themselves, it needs more accommodation just for them, Bahr demands.
In Bavaria, the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees.
When asked if they knew about a similar project as in Munich in their area of responsibility, some answer no.
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Even in Swabia, women who have refugeed alone are not housed separately, says Karl-Heinz Meyer, the government's press spokesman.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower and Middle Franconia, in some shared accommodation there are floors or own houses only for single women and their children.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodations exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
In a study published for the committee, it says: "It is very important that men and women are accommodated separately."
“If privacy is lacking or if men and women are housed together, there may be – more continuous – violence against women.”
The washrooms in particular should be separate and easily accessible to women, according to the study.
How much the women feel this need for protection can be seen in the rush, which is on the house in Munich.
"Since it's been said that we exist, we've got a long waiting list," Bahr says.
You could easily open a second house.
