For Moscow, this is a matter of course, which itself has a deep-seated fear of regime change.
The summit meeting in this splendid palace by the sea enabled Russia and Turkey to represent one, as one analyst once described to me, "alliance of outsiders": two countries that feel disowned by the West and feel badly treated and now ally.
Nevertheless, despite the public reconciliation, there are still great differences between the two.
The biggest difference is Syria, where Moscow recently gave itself the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides.
It could be significant that after nearly three hours of initial talks, both presidents testified at the press conference that they hadn't even stripped the issue.
The president of Turkey deliberately avoided responding to a question about their differences, while Putin decided to emphasize them.
