Community, spirit, health: Singing does seniors good
The singing has accompanied Ursel Kipp all her life: As a young girl she was in the school choir, in the teacher training studies she took the subject of music, and today the 78-year-old sings in a senior choir.
"Singing moves me - emotionally and physically," she describes.
After a rehearsal, she feels balanced, cheerful and overall more alive, she says.
By the way, she does something good for her health and her mind.
Because singing is a great hobby for seniors from several perspectives, says Erhard Hackler of the German Senior League.
Most seniors sing in the choir and share the joy of the music with like-minded people, Hackler describes.
Through regular gathering, seniors can make and maintain social contacts.
Because often social and family structures dissolve in old age, a choir is then an ideal opportunity to spend time with other people.
Ursel Kipp has also had this experience in her choir: "To agree and organize, to be able to rely on others and learn from each other - a choir is a very special form of being together".
Singing can be exhausting in a positive sense, Hackler says.
Seniors train deep and controlled breathing.
If you regularly demand your lungs, you will not get out of breath so quickly in everyday life.
Even when it comes to preserving the sound of the voice in old age, singing is an optimal hobby.
Singing often has a very special effect on the elderly, says Ursula Lenz of the Federal Association of Senior Citizens' Organisations.
In the older generations, singing together had a much higher priority, it was part of everyday life, both in school and in leisure, she explains.
Lenz often observes that singing or listening to songs awakens many memories in older people, often combined with positive feelings of their youth.
Through song lyrics and especially melodies, even dementia-sick people revent long-ago events.
When singing, the head is also required to perform a special way, explains Lenz.
At the same time, to focus on your own voice and on a predetermined rhythm and to adapt to the other singers - this is a great cognitive challenge.
Especially older people who live alone, practice not only focusing on themselves.
Another positive aspect is the recognition that one experiences by singing in the choir, Hackler says.
An enthusiastic audience is great praise.
Self-esteem also grows through singing in the choir.
Showing yourself: If I practice for something for a long time, I get better and grow beyond myself - this experience strengthens.
So there are plenty of good reasons to start singing.
If you want to try a new hobby, you should not hesitate - even if you think you have little talent, advises Lenz.
You don't sing alone - with 50 singing people, who hears when a sound goes wrong?
In search of the right offer, seniors have different options, Hackler says.
If someone from the circle of acquaintances sings in a senior choir, you can simply join.
Many cities also offer overviews of the choirs in the area.
If you want to sing in a church choir, you can contact the church leader directly.
Many senior choirs can also be found over the Internet.
Those who do not have access to the Internet can ask family, friends or neighbors for help with Internet research.
If you want to sing, you should definitely join a choir, advises Hackler.
Singing is good for the soul and has something liberating - this applies to all ages.
