In a previous study, the research team had already found that the duration and pitch of the kitten screams differs with the urgency of their need for help.
A total of nine adult hangovers and eight cats from the animal husbandry of the MHH were observed.
They were played, on the one hand, shouts of little ones who were taken out of the litter box for three minutes and separated from mother and siblings.
On the other hand, they were confronted with screams of more excited kittens, which were additionally lifted up.
The researchers consider their results to be meaningful despite the small sample.
"All the females, even those who have not yet had their own offspring, responded to the screams in a differentiated way," Konerding said.
They turned around to the loudspeaker faster when this calls of the very more aroused kittens played out.
This ability may be innate or develop with sexual maturity.
"A surprise was that the males reacted at all," the biologist said.
In the past, scientists have already examined the reactions of women and men to baby noises on several occasions in humans.
Also, some studies showed that women reacted more sensitively to infants, whether they were already mothers or not, reported the biologist Marina Scheumann.
