In the midst of the rage of the Olympics, the Zen of the trampoline
Wherever you are, whatever time it is, it's the Olympics.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inevitable, a frenzied relay race between competition and pursuit.
It's as if the Olympic torch itself is a burning rod served from crossbow shooter to swimmer to gymnast to triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read a newspaper, or listen to your neighbor's conversation in the coffe shop, without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky or the dispute between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
