Kepler measures rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades' star cluster
The latest mission with the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete catalog of rotation rates under the stars of the Pleiades' star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars rotate in the cluster at different rates and what the rotation periods with planet formation are related to the formation of the planet.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at the Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, said in a press release.
The star cluster of the Pleiades is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this star cluster, which formed around 125 million years ago, now reach adulthood.
They're turning the fastest now.
At peak rotation rates, these ripening stars emit large amounts of star winds.
Since these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
When a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by detecting the time between the appearance of a recognizable starspot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars spinning more slowly pirouettes than smaller ones.
"In the "Ballet" of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars," Rebull said.
Because the star cluster of the Pleiades is so close, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The star cluster of the Pleiades provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older," Rebull said.
There is still a lot ahead of us about which we would like to learn more about how the how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rates and, so to speak, hang up their "dance shoes".
Rebull and her colleagues have reported in detail in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades, which will soon appear in the Astronomical Journal.
