Data theft: How perfidiously, hackers extort their ransom
Programmers of blackmail malware are currently targeting companies - and are successful in the process.
According to a recent survey by malware defense specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America, the UK and Germany, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been victims of an attack with blackmail software at least once in the past twelve months, sometimes several times.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies were already the target of ransomware blackmail.
40 percent of the victims willingly paid the ransoms demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to use the attacked systems and data again.
The perpetrators specialize their blackmail software, according to the observations of Malwarebytes, increasingly in attacks on company networks.
If they are successful there, the ransom to be potentially extorted is significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently observing a frighteningly rapid evolution of the malware," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with the "world".
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send advertising.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
First, private users were the target, but the switch to company attacks has taken place in recent months terrifyingly fast.
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern: Once active on a victim’s computer, she searches specifically for recently changed files such as Word, Excel or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files encrypt the ransomware and permanently delete the originals.
Subsequently, the software presents the demands of the blackmailers.
To get the end-key code to the files, victims have to transfer money - mostly in the form of the crypto currency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project databases without which production is at a standstill.
Accordingly, the damage is higher if a ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported revenue losses due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely interrupt the business activity, in one case, people were in danger of life.
In Germany, hospitals have already been victims of attacks on several occasions, the patients of which can be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always tell the victims: don't pay, you just promote the problem," Kleczynski explains.
Yet 80 to 90 percent of companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to reject the demand of the perpetrators in the face of standstill in the company.
The hackers, in turn, know this and try everything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, F-Secure’s security researchers examined the user interfaces and contact with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion: The perpetrators are actually trying to build some kind of customer service to take more money.
They explain to their victims via chat how to pay via Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites or decrypt sample files for free.
And if private individuals are redeemed after payments of a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-figure sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free gains from ransomware blackmail, the hackers are becoming more and more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of the antivirus provider Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware approximately within a week."
More likely, however, are three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malware to the actual blackmailers in the form of a software builder.
The previous malware kits were created by buying the malware itself, consulting and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price between $1000 and $10,000.
"Included is a customization tool, so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then look for more hackers to spread the freshly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log in to one of the forums underground, buy the set from a criminal and commission another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"Usually, the criminals then commission spammers to spread," Wisniewski explains.
The risk of ransomware is now known to many companies that better back up their data.
More than 50 percent of company IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to ward off ransomware using file backups and scanner software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful extortion, the perpetrators instead threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
Thus, the damage potential is still many times higher than before, depending on the type of data.
In the future, the perpetrators could also target completely new targets in the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get an internet-connected thermostat under their control.
In the middle of winter, the activation of such a blocked heating system could well be worth a ransom to many a victim.
If the perpetrators then block an entire production line in a factory instead of the heating in the future, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
