Old buildings, a few lime trees, in between a remnant of cobblestones: Rigaer Straße in Berlin-Friedrichshain does not seem like it at first glance, but the police count it among the "dangerous places" of the city.
If you walk along the road from east to west, you will pass playgrounds, a newly painted kindergarten and an organic shop.
On the facade of a gray house, someone sprayed "ugly!"
Opposite a Lidl, which is also to be demolished soon, is already being built: By 2017, a house with high windows and 133 new rental apartments is to be built here.
However, articles about this "trendy district", as the responsible real estate company Friedrichshain calls, are preferably illustrated with burning cars in recent weeks.
The reason is the house with the number 94: once it was occupied, meanwhile the residents have leases, on the ground floor, however, rooms are still occupied and are used for events.
Since the beginning of the year, the Berlin interior senator Henkel in particular had repeatedly advocated a crackdown by the police against the project, calling the area a "no-go zone" for police officers and the 94 a starting point for autonomous violence.
After on the 22. June the rooms on the ground floor, the Kadterschmiede, had been cleared with 300 police officers, the police patroled for three weeks according to official statements with 30 to 40 officers and three crew cars on site, cordoned off parts of the road and stopped visitors from entering the house with the number 94.
Meanwhile, construction workers renovated the rooms on behalf of the unknown homeowners.
On the 13th July, a Berlin administrative court ruled that the eviction had been illegal, and a day later, police and construction workers pulled away under the cheers of sympathizers and local residents.
This summer afternoon, the street seems peaceful: parents go for a walk with children, people sit on the sidewalk in front of the houses in the sun, others talk in front of the Späti.
In the immediate vicinity of the house projects are a primary school and kindergartens.
Left-wing violence is not the main concern of many local residents: Kerstin Neugebauer, who has lived in the neighbourhood since 1999, and Jana*, who raises three children here, are especially annoyed by the police presence.
With the residents of the home projects, they share the concern about rising rents and gentrification.
It does not sound like a neighborhood that mostly wanted police protection from vandaling leftists.
The moat that the Berlin interior senator and the police open between squatters and their neighbors apparently does not exist.
Friedrichshain in the east of Berlin was actually a traditional working-class district, which still has a low average income and high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city.
House occupations and the residential projects born from them have also long been part of the neighborhood: in 1990, numerous houses were occupied in the former GDR, including almost the entire Mainzer Straße very close to the Riga.
While the Mainzer had been cleared under a large police force in a real street battle, many of the projects in the Riga were legalized and are still inhabited today by the people who occupied them 26 years ago.
At the same time, the district has increasingly become a magnet for tourists and electoral Berliners from all over the world in recent years: residents from GDR times and former squatters now share their neighbourhood with them.
This is also evident in the case of rents, which have risen by almost 60 percent since 2009 for new rentals.
Many of the new buildings in the Riga are attacked as symbols for this development: they can be recognized by thrown-in discs or freshly painted facades, which have been pelted with paint bags.
No other street has been mentioned so often this year along with the words "left-autonomous violence."
One reason that not all neighbors see this as a problem could be that they are not necessarily affected by crime: According to statistics, crimes such as assault are almost exclusively directed against police officers.
Most of the offences account for property damage, which tends to hit new buildings and newly renovated homes.
For Kerstin Neugebauer, who has lived in a tenement building next to the controversial 94 for 17 years, there can be no talk of uncertainty.
As for acts of violence, she is appeasing: the people in the 94 are their neighbors, they certainly were not.
Even the famous burning cars have not existed directly in the Riga for a long time.
For the studied architect, her street is not a criminal focal point, on the contrary: "Here you help each other, live together on the street and get more from each other than elsewhere".
Neugebauer deliberately moved into Riga Street - and stayed.
That’s why it was so important to her that the residents get their street back: from the police, politics and the media, who suddenly claimed the sovereignty of interpretation over the district in July.
But in the eyes of residents like Neugebauer, the road is still taken away from them: through faceless new buildings in former construction gaps that displace the old inhabitants.
"These are ultimately condominiums that are not interesting for many here - people who are not so well-heeled live here," she says.
“I absolutely cannot approve of violence and destruction.”
But what should you do if no one ever listens to you?
There is frustration on all sides, including the police and the residents.
For newcomers who are angry about color bombs, Kerstin Neugebauer has little understanding: The house projects and the left scene belonged to the neighborhood.
Anyone who moves here should be aware of this - just like someone who moves to a pub district can complain badly about noise there.
